	abstract = {Social economists and environmental researchers all over the globe are involved in how socioeconomic aspects and ambient air effluence affect the health of people. Despite wide research studies, the spatial heterogeneity consequences on public health remain poorly understood. Many emerging nations and the global world as a whole are becoming increasingly interested in the issue of environmental contamination. Inadvertently causing significant environmental issues, the recent rapid urbanization and industrialization that have been observed throughout the world have contributed to expanding socioeconomic developments that have resulted in the overexploitation of natural resources. This chapter is an effort to outline the socioeconomic effects of environmental contamination on our outdoor environment. In particular, we concentrated further on the main types of contamination that are extensively acknowledged as global public health issues, such as air pollution, counting its effects and how it has acted as a barrier to social and economic progress by placing great strain on resources and the environment. Several types of interventions together with potential means of guaranteeing environmental quality and sustainability that would benefit public health and well-being were recommended. Research on the socioeconomic state of urban air pollution and its causes is essential because it contributes to a better consideration of the mutual response mechanisms between socioeconomic systems and outdoor pollution. Understanding these processes can help in the creation and application of effective environmental regulations, which will ultimately enhance the standard of urbanization development.},
